		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper01</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Object Grammars: Compositional and Bidirectional Mapping between Text and Graphs</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TijsvanderStorm.html">Tijs van der Storm</a>, <a href="../profile/WilliamRCook.html">William R. Cook</a>, <a href="../profile/AlexLoh.html">Alex Loh</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_2">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_2</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2012s/paper04.html"><em>The design and implementation of Object Grammars</em></a> (SLE 2012 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It introduces “object grammars” as a meta-language to define syntax together with mappings between text and object graphs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> A central concern is compositionality—how grammars/mappings can be combined and embedded modularly.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The contribution supports bidirectional parsing/pretty-printing at runtime, i.e., executable mappings between representations.
</li></ul></li></ul>
